Using for loop to determine the range for the cluster.

Using KMeans from sklearn to perfrom KMeans clustering. The n_cluster parameter is in built in Kmeans to specify the number of clusters. Fitting refers to adjusting the parameters in the model to improve accuracy. The process involves running an algorithm on data for which the target variable (labeled data) is known to produce a machine learning model. Then, the models outcomes are compared to the real, observed values of the target variable to determine the accuracy.

In [586]:
WCSS1 = []
for i in range(1, 11): 
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i)
    kmeans.fit(dataset_1.iloc[:,0:3]) 
    WCSS1.append(kmeans.inertia_)

Contingency Matrix

A Contingency Table is used to display the frequency distribution of class labels among a clustering.

Contingency tables classify outcomes for one variable in rows and the other in columns.

importing Contingency Matrix from sklearn library

Using for loop to determine the range for the cluster.

Using KMeans from sklearn to perfrom KMeans clustering. The n_cluster parameter is in built in Kmeans to specify the number of clusters. Fitting refers to adjusting the parameters in the model to improve accuracy. The process involves running an algorithm on data for which the target variable (labeled data) is known to produce a machine learning model. Then, the models outcomes are compared to the real, observed values of the target variable to determine the accuracy.

In [609]:
wcss2 = []

    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i)
    kmeans.fit(dataset_2.iloc[:,0:3]) 
    wcss2.append(kmeans.inertia_)

Scaling the GDP column

Feature scaling is about transforming the values of different numerical features to fall within a similar range like each other. It is used to prevent the supervised learning models from getting biased toward a specific range of values. It is done so that all features can share the same scale and avoid loss in accuracy

In [768]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range =[0,1])
values = scaler.fit_transform(np.array(df_world['GDP']).reshape(-1,1))
df_world['GDP'] = values.reshape(1,-1)[0]
In [769]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn import metrics
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage

In case of normalizing the training and test data set, the MinMaxScaler estimator will fit on the training data set and the same estimator will be used to transform both training and the test data set. The MinMaxscaler is a type of scaler that scales the minimum and maximum values to be 0 and 1 respectively.
